Unlike most host countries in the world, what Uganda does is provide economic opportunities for refugees.
Grant them the right to work and the freedom to move.
The result of this is astonishing, both for the refugees and the host countries.
In the capital of Uganda, Kampala, we found that twenty-one percent of refugees start their own businesses and employ others, with forty percent of the employees being nationals of the host country.
In other words, refugees are creating jobs for the citizens of the host country.
Even in refugee camps, we found examples of vibrant and thriving entrepreneurial ventures.
