The economist Alvin Roth created the concept of matching markets, where the preferences of both parties determine the final match.
My colleagues Will Jones and Alexis Tate-Bowen are researching how to apply this concept to address the refugee issue. They ask refugees to rank their preferred countries while also allowing countries to rank the types of refugees they wish to accept based on criteria such as skills or language. Ultimately, the two rankings are matched.
Of course, you need to establish quotas in terms of diversity and vulnerability, but this is a method that can enhance the likelihood of successful matching.
